Introduction
Nowadays, micro-scaled flow (flow with typical geometric size of about 100 microns, also known as microfluidics1) is often met and widely used in biomedicine, chemical reaction, environmental protection, food safety, cell biology, pharmaceutical industry, etc. Influenced by scale effects, microscaled flow behaviors can be significantly different from that in macro-scaled flow. For liquids, the most significant impact is the sharp increase of the surface-area-to-volume ratio, which makes the surface force of liquids more important and the volume force almost negligible. This also makes the interface effect of solid walls on liquids significantly increase under certain conditions, such as the generation of double layers, electrophoresis and electroosmosis phenomena when applying an electric field to the micro-scaled flows. Moreover, as the scale decreases, the relative effect of inertia to viscosity decreases. The Reynolds number (Re), which represents the relative importance of the inertial and the viscous effects, is much lower in micro-scaled flows than that in macro-scaled flows. In many areas of microfluidics, such as the separation of reaction products,2 the flow is often regular and stable as the inertial effect is weak in a microchannel, which is beneficial to the precise control of the flow. There also exist some applications such as microrheology
and particle manipulation that utilize the inertial effect. For example, effects of inertial are important for performing measurements of low viscosity fluids in the extensional rheometers.3,4 For the particles with a diameter of several microns or nanometers, inertial effect can affect the particle dynamics tremendously, leading to the emerging of a new field, i.e. inertial microfluidics, which refer to the manipulation of particles, such as mixing, focusing, ordering, separating and concentrating particles. The exhausted work on inertial microfluidics can be found from the wellwritten review papers.5,6 As the present paper focuses on the influence of the elastic effect caused by the flow of the working medium itself and its application in
