many fields, the following introduces the uniqueness of viscoelastic fluid and its potential applications in microfluidics. Fluids can be generally classified into two basic types, Newtonian fluids and non-Newtonian fluids according to their rheological properties. Viscoelastic fluid is a kind of non-Newtonian fluid, with both viscosity and elasticity, and its mechanical behavior is related not only to the shear or extensional strain rate, but also to the flow history, i.e. memory effect. This unique memory effect makes viscoelastic fluids behave quite differently from Newtonian fluids. Some unique phenomena with viscoelastic fluids include the rod-climbing effect (Weissenberg effect),7 tubeless siphon phenomenon,8 extrudate swelling effect,9 bouncing liquid jet effect (Kaye Effect),10 turbulent drag reduction,11 shear thinning/thickening,12 and so on. The fluids that exhibit viscoelastic properties can be mainly divided into three groups, high molecule-weight polymer solutions, aqueous solutions of some surfactants and polymer melts.13 Generally speaking, different types of micro-structures embedded in the fluids result in a variety of different fluid behaviors. The researches on polymer melts are not in the scope of this paper, because the temperature involved in polymer melts is generally higher than the melting point of polymer materials. This review paper focuses on the cases under normal pressure and temperature. For the viscoelastic effect of polymer melts, we refer the readers to literature.14–16 In the following, we take the polymer solutions and surfactant solutions as examples to illustrate the elastic effects of viscoelastic fluids from a microscopic point of view. The molecular structures of polymer and additive are schematically shown in Figure 1. Polymers are composed of many monomers, which are randomly distributed in the solution at low concentrations, but aggregate with each other to form a flexible network structure over critical concentrations.17 The molecular structure of polymers has several types, including linear, branched and reticulated types, each of which has different rheological properties.18 Surfactant molecules consist of hydrophilic head and hydrophobic tail, which form spherical, rod-like and reticular micelles at different concentrations in aqueous
solution.19,20 The flexible network structure (or micelle structure) of polymer solutions (or surfactant solutions) at different concentrations will coil or stretch depending on the applied deformation. This enables viscoelastic fluids to exhibit elastic effects at the macro level, i.e. the flow depends on its flow history as mentioned previously. The coil-stretch motion pattern of viscoelastic molecular structure can be compared to that of solid springs, based on which different models were proposed to describe the molecular structure of viscoelastic fluid, e.g. the Pearl-Spring dumbbell model. Consequently, the dynamic behavior of viscoelastic fluids can be simulated from microscale approaches (e.g. Brownian dynamics) or macroscopic approaches by different constitutive models (e.g. Oldroyd-B). It depends on whether the purpose of the study is the interaction between molecules of viscoelastic fluid or the flow of viscoelastic fluid at macro scale.12 The existence of elastic nonlinearity brings about various interesting flow phenomena in viscoelastic fluid flow, especially in microfluidics where the inertial nonlinearity can be negligible while the elastic nonlinearity can dominate the flow. Specifically, purely elasticity-induced instability and turbulence can occur in microchannels when the elastic nonlinearity is strong enough. As stated above, limited by geometric scale, Re of the flow in microchannels is usually so small (Re < 100 or even much smaller than 1,21 inertial microfluidics will be discussed in subsection particle manipulation). Under such circumstance, the Newtonian fluids flow tends to be laminar and steady. However, for viscoelastic fluids, it has been found that the flow instability and ‘‘turbulent-like’’ motion can be induced solely by nonlinear elastic effect at an extremely low Re when the Weissenberg number (Wi, a dimensionless number characterizing the strength of elasticity) exceeds the critical value,22 which are named as purely elastic instability and elastic turbulence. The occurrence of the purely elastic instability and turbulence of viscoelastic fluid at an extremely low Re can find many applications in microfluidic devices. For instance, an efficient mixing can be achieved through the use of viscoelastic fluid in a rhombic-shape microchannel at Re 0.3 and
