Elastic instability and turbulence in microchannels
With the increase of Wi or De, the transitions of viscoelastic fluid flow induced by purely-elastic effect include laminar state, elastic instability and elastic turbulence. The elastic instability refers to the destabilizing flow resulting from increasing elastic effect, which exhibits the stable or unstable characteristic, and can be analogous to the transitional flow state induced by the inertial instability. The elastic turbulence is the saturated flow state after the ultimately transition of elastic instability, which can be analogous to the inertial turbulence with large Re.
Elastic instability in microchannels
Since Rayleigh first proposed the concept of elasticityinduced instability in 1880,42 viscoelastic fluids have attracted numerous researchers’ attention for nearly one and a half century, and the research boom has not diminished yet. Elastic instability has been extensively studied in classical shear flow devices.43–46 The results of viscoelastic fluid flow in concentric rotating cylinders (Taylor-Couette setup, abbreviated as T-C) show that there are wave structures propagating in both the radial and axial directions, and the wavelength and wave number are determined by the curvature, time and Wi. Detailed discussions of the flow structure are referred to the literature.47,48 For coneand-plate and two-parallel-disks geometries, when Wi is large enough, elastic instability occurs and are
characterized by Bernoulli spirals45 and Archimedean spirals46 vortex, respectively. For a long time, it was believed that the underlying mechanism for the onset of purely elastic instability is related to the streamline curvature and the generation of large hoop stress, represented in the PakdelMcKinley criterion for determining the instability threshold.49,50 McKinley et al.49 derived from the linear stability theory that elastic instability can only occur in channels with a certain curvature. While later studies on nonlinear instability theory showed that elastic instability can also occur in a straight path with no curvature, provided the destabilization of upstream flow is strong enough.51,52 Pan et al.52 experimentally demonstrated that the flow of viscoelastic fluid in the straight channel can also be nonlinearly unstable. They designed a straight microchannel with a series of cylinders at the very beginning of the channel for introducing flow perturbation (Figure 2(a)). Their results showed that the instability can occur, provided the upstream disturbance is sufficiently strong, which can be modulated by the number of cylinders in the upstream (Figure 2(b)). In addition to shear flow, elastic instability also attracts lots of attention in extensional flows, which in general include jet flows, variable cross-section flows, and flows with stagnation points, etc.53 Taking the cross-slot flow as a typical instance, elastic instability in extensional flow is described below. Viscoelastic fluid flow exhibits two types of elastic instabilities in a micro cross-slot channel, which have been verified by both experimental and numerical studies.54–56 Sousa et al.44 demonstrated that as Wi increases, the flow undergoes three regimes: steady symmetric flow, steady asymmetric flow (first instability, snapshot II in Figure 3(a)) and time-dependent flow (second instability, snapshot III in Figure 3(a)).
