Elastic turbulence in microchannels
It has been two decades since the first report on elastic turbulence by Groisman and Steinberg.22 So far, numerous researches on this subject have been carried out to obtain insight into its underlying mechanism as well as to realize its application. The elastic turbulence was described as the flow regime after ultimate transition from elastic instability regime, with some characteristics, such as significant growth of drag resistance, a wide range of energy spectrum, and fluctuating vortex structures random in time but smooth in space. For viscoelastic fluid in swirling flows (e.g. flow between two parallel plates and T-C flow), the drag resistance was growing significantly with Wi exceeding the critical value, and even can reach tens of times that of Newtonian fluids (Figure 4(a) and (b)). Besides, the drag resistance curves with Wi’s increasing and decreasing are different, which indicates that the elastic instability is a hysteretic transition.58 As for the power spectra of elastic turbulence in swirling flows, the velocity power spectra decay exponents of flow between two plates and in curvilinear channel were between 3 and 4 (Figure 4(c) and (d)). These values are
smaller than the velocity power spectra decay exponent of inertia subregion of inertia turbulence ( 5/ 3), which implies that elastic turbulence shows a faster decay law of the velocity power spectra. Additionally, Berti et al.59 and Zhang et al.37 obtained the elastic turbulence power spectra in two-dimensional Kolmogorov flow and threedimensional rectilinear channel flow of viscoelastic fluids by direct numerical simulation (DNS) and their numerical findings also lied between 3 and 4. Note that the velocity power spectra exponent of elastic turbulence in T-C flow was 1.1 and 2.2 at low and high frequencies, respectively, which were obviously different from the other two flows. The reasons need to be further studied. As mentioned above, elastic turbulence and inertial turbulence share strong similarity in their overall behaviors but with inherently different physical mechanisms. The similarity is shown through the fact that both inertial and elastic turbulence possess scaling laws and intermittent characteristics.60,61 Apart from the energy spectrum distribution discussed above, there are many other differences. For instance, energy dissipation of inertial turbulence occurs mainly at high frequency and small scale, while energy dissipation of elastic turbulence mainly occurs at low frequency and large scale. Therefore, the energy cascade theory for inertial turbulence is not fully applicable to elastic turbulence. In addition, the energy of turbulent structures in elastic turbulence is from the elastic deformation of the microstructures in viscoelastic fluids (i.e. the stretching and relaxation of the molecular structures correspond to the energy storage and release respectively), while the energy in inertial turbulence is transmitted from the large-scale turbulence structure to the small-scale structure.62
