Application of viscoelastic fluid flows in microfluidics
Micro-mixer
Micro-mixing has important applications in many fields, such as homogenization of reagent solutions, nucleic acid sequencing, dilution of drug solutions in chemical and biological reactions.63,64 Mixing is essentially a physical process to achieve uniform distribution of solutes in different components. There are two mechanisms for the realization, namely, diffusive mass transfer and convective mass transfer. Diffusive mass transfer refers to the mixing of molecules by random and irregular thermal motion. Convective mass transfer refers to the breaking up of different solute groups into small clusters under the action of convection, and consequently the contact area between different components is increased and the diffusion of molecules to achieve the purpose of mixing is prompted. A dimensionless Peclet number (cf. Table 1), which represents the relative importance of
the advection transport rate over diffusive transport rate, is often introduced. Pe is generally larger than 10 for typical microfluidic flow conditions, which means that the diffusion process acts more slowly than the hydrodynamic transport.21 As mentioned above, the flow state of Newtonian fluid in micro-scaled flow is normally laminar and steady. The mixing process mainly depends on diffusion mechanism, and a very low efficiency can be expected. Take a protein of 70 kDa, for example; it will take 1 s to diffuse 10 mm but more than 10 days to diffuse a centimeter.21 For most researches, such a long mixing time is not accessible and alternative solutions must be sought. Therefore, various active and passive methods are put forward to strengthen mixing in microfluidics. External forces such as magnetic field,65 sound field66 and electric field67 are used in active means. On the contrary, passive method of enhancing mixing effect is achieved mainly via the changing of physical properties of fluid and the channel’s structures. In comparison, passive micro-mixer is simple, economical and relatively easy to achieve, and
